Children's International Summer Visit program included high school children from Springfield, MA, Philadelphia, France, Norway, Sweden, Jordan, China, Brazil, Columbia

First visit of the season. Chris helped with all forms of the protocol including plant identification for the habitat assessment. Chris mentioned that he has seen a decline in feral cats due to populations of coyotes increasing in Atlanta. He keeps his cats inside.

This morning was windy and colder. Two birds bounced out of the net, with several birds also flying over the net or only perching on the fence. Jason was very involved during the point count and banding, and his daughter also watched us band before going to school. Callen, Jason's wife, was helpful in getting access to neighbors property and asked about how to increase biodiversity/ habitat value in their yard.

Anne was present for the whole visit, and a huge help. She feels more incline to resight data instead of nesting, as well as reached out to neighbors to discuss color bands resights. NOCA were hard to lure in, as well as TUTI call worked to lure in 2 other birds.

Visit was great, best success was in the backyard and rushing feeders birds into thenets. Bob was involved, but in and out of the house, only involved with banding. He mentioned that the website is difficult to use and is a barrier to data entry. He has 50 data points that have yet to be entered.

Overall visit was ok. The participant spread seed all over her driveway, which made it hard to have a central area to focus birds into net. As far as I know, she doesn't have a feeder or binoculars and a hard time i.d.ing birds/ didn't know the focal species. I used the resight foray mainly to practice iding birds, as well as discuss how best to resight them. Property had limited understory.
Lots of construction nearby, less nearby tree cover than in past years. Sandy knows her backyard birds well as well as is an avid birder. She participated with everything but the habitat assessment.
Placed two twelve meters and one six meter in the back. Moved one six meter to the front yard to try and catch SOSP and AMRO.

Ended visit early due to thunderstorms that started at 9:15. I will return later this week to finish resighting and habitat assessment. Miriam was a huge help in describing the setup from past years, as well as record keeping. She asked lots of questions about what the different measurements meant, especially what blood was used for, and was overall thrilled to be there.

Dianne was great and enthusiastic, she had to start work at 9:30, otherwise she would have participated in resighting etc. All of the birds were caught in the front yard by the feeders, no playback was used in the front.
Dottie was a huge help, scribing as well as watching the nets while I was processing birds. Placed nets in a shallow V around the feeders, which seemed to be effective in catching birds.

Participant was interested but busy, left to go to Home Depot during banding. Bill had questions in between banding and the habitat assessment, but was not present during activities. Interestingly, he had snags that he kept in his backyard, but did not seem terribly interested in submitting data.

Saw a Cooper's Hawk while setting up nets, as well as neighbor dogs barking incessantly. Birds were most responsive to chickadee scold, rather than the feeder. Participants were helpful in watching for nets from inside the house.

Placed nets by blueberry bushes, GRCA have been heard by family, yet not heard today. In the past blueberries were used to attract birds to the nets. Caught a SOSP with severe leg mites that was unable to be banded.
Participant normally takes part in multiple activities, but was caring for a newborn at the time of the visit.

Participants asked quetsions in regards to what the blood sample was used for, species identification and song identification, if males and females always caught together, if they reuse the same nest and or nest sites, what if the purpose of different calls in bird, as well as why do birds mob other birds.

Conducted a partial visit as the homeschool group showed up at 10:00. There were maybe 8 children, with 6 chaperones, ages 4-10 for the children. One CARW escaped banding. Children were mostly interested in how to catch birds, how to age them, what was the point of color bands. Did not collect blood as one child was severely concerned over bird safety.

Participant asked questions in regards to if females are territorial, how large are cardinals territories, what is the purpose of blood, why do birds have brood patches. Participant had not seen a BP before.
Slightly raining/ misting. Banded recap cardinal with deformed bill, as well as captured and released a chickadee unbanded due to leg mites.

Participant was helpful at all stages. Asked questions related to whether birds stay in neighborhood, if local birds have slight migratory pattersn (she stopped seeing banded birds at her feeder after Winter) and whether birds stay paired for life.

Helped participant with bird id and song id. Emily was curious about how to deseign backyard habitats, and which native plants were the best to plant, as well as how to learn calls, and why we chose which particular focal species. Participant was very concerned of bird safety.

Participant knew yards birds  id, the adjoining neighbors whose property they had used in the past didn't wake up until around 8. Diane recommendas moving the nets next year to the D'andreas two houses down. Birds quiet due to light mist and slight breeze, no feeders due to rats.

Participants contributed as much as they could (elderly and recovering from stroke), stayed inside to not disturb birds at feeder. Helpful with describing net position and where birds fly in from. Placed nets by feeder and flushed birds into nets, after sun hit the nets making them visible.
Released 2 Cach, and 1 TUTI due to leg mites. Participant was working, but participated when I caught a bird.

participantEngagement: 5: Participant contributed during all visit activities
notes: Overcast, cool, & breezy; making nests readily visible. Much of site area was pasture, and one area fronted busy highway, so limited the foray area. Non-target spp captured: 1 BRTH, 1 HOFI, 1 BLJA, 1 NOMO (recap of newly banded male PX,P). Evidence of mild, possible avian pox infection on cardinals (warty, reddish growths on toes only, some starting to scab over), but on no other species. Advised participant to scrub & sanitize feeders, baths, and sheperd's crooks with 5% bleach solution and remove standing water sources to reduce mosquito breeding habitat (per USGS Field Manual of Wildlife Diseases). .
